  <section class="faq-section section-pad">
    <div class="container faq-inner">
      <div class="faq-header reveal">
        <span class="eyebrow">Common Questions</span>
        <h2 class="section-heading faq-heading">Process Questions</h2>
        <p class="faq-intro">Straight answers to the questions we hear most often.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">

        <details class="faq-item reveal delay-1">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            How long does the recovery process take?
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </span>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>It depends on the debtor and the account. Some debtors respond to the first formal demand and settle within days. Others require weeks of follow-up, tracing, or bureau listing before they engage. There is no fixed timeframe — what we can promise is that every account receives continuous, structured attention until it is either collected or formally closed.</p>
            <p>We don't give up. As long as an account remains active on our portfolio, it is being worked. We'll keep you updated monthly so you always know the status of each account.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item reveal delay-2">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            What happens if a debtor contacts my business directly?
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </span>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>This does happen, especially at the start of the process when debtors are startled by formal demand letters. If a debtor contacts you directly, the best course of action is to let them know that the account is now being handled by Any Debt Collections and direct them to contact us.</p>
            <p>Please let us know immediately if this happens — it's important that we're aware of any direct contact so we can update our records and adjust our approach accordingly. Do not agree to any payment plans directly, as this can complicate the recovery process.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item reveal delay-3">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            Can I add new accounts after the initial handover?
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
            </span>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Absolutely. Most of our clients add accounts on an ongoing basis as new debts become overdue. There is no minimum or maximum number of accounts — you can hand over a single account or a hundred at a time. Our process handles both.</p>
            <p>Simply send us the account details using the same format as the initial handover, and we'll load them into the portfolio and begin the recovery programme. New accounts appear in your next monthly report so you can see exactly when they were loaded and what initial contact has been made.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

